<P><A NAME="1">NOT FOR RELEASE - FOR PLANNING PURPOSES ONLY</P><A NAME="2">AG</P>

<P><A NAME="3">WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 9, 2000</P>(202) <A NAME="4">514-2007</P>

<P>WWW.USDOJ.GOV	</P>TDD (202) 514-1888</P><BR>


<P ALIGN="CENTER"><STRONG><U>DEPUTY ATTORNEY GENERAL HOLDER TO HONOR CIVIL </U></STRONG></CENTER>

<CENTER><STRONG><U>RIGHTS PIONEER RUBY BRIDGES AT CEREMONY </U></STRONG></CENTER>

<CENTER><STRONG><U>AT CORCORAN GALLERY OF ART</U></STRONG></CENTER></P>


<BR>
<P>	WASHINGTON, D.C. - Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder will
join in honoring Ruby Bridges on the 40<SUP>th</SUP> anniversary of her historic
walk into a formerly all-white school, which began the integration of
the New Orleans public school system. To commemorate this
anniversary, the Deputy Attorney General will make Ms. Bridges an
Honorary U.S. Marshal at Thursday's ceremony.</P>


<P>	The ceremony will be held at the Corcoran Gallery of Art where
Norman Rockwell's depiction of this incident, entitled <EM>The Problem We
all Live With,</EM> is on temporary exhibition.  The ceremony, which
begins at 4:00 p.m., will be held in the Frances and Armand Hammer
Auditorium.  This event coincides with the 17<SUP>th</SUP> Annual convention of
the National Black Prosecutors' Association.</P>


<P><STRONG>                                                    WHEN</STRONG>: Thursday,
August 10, 2000</P>

<P>	                                                       4:00
p.m.</P>

<P>                                                                      
                                                   </P>


<P><STRONG>                                                  WHERE</STRONG>: Corcoran
Gallery of Art </P>

<P>                                                                   
Frances and Armand Hammer Auditorium</P>

<P>	                                                        New
York Avenue and 17<SUP>th</SUP> Street, N.W.</P>

<P>	                                                       
Washington, D.C. </P>




